This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring March 31, 2015, as César Chávez Day. The proclamation honors César Chávez, a labor leader and civil rights activist, for his work in fighting for fair wages, workers' rights, and social justice. Chávez, the son of migrant workers, founded the United Farm Workers union and organized protests and boycotts to improve the conditions of farm workers. The proclamation calls on Americans to observe the day by engaging in service, community, and education programs to honor Chávez's legacy. It also highlights the ongoing need to address issues such as immigration reform, workers' rights, and economic equality.